{
  "format": "wspradar.config",
  "schema_version": 1,
  "profile": {
    "id": "zander_tx_buddy",
    "title": {
      "en": "Prof. Zander et al. TX Antenna Comparison: Short Portable Vertical vs 5/8 λ Vertical"
    },
    "description": {
      "en": "[Publication: Zander, J. (2022). Simple HF antenna efficiency comparisons using the WSPR system](https://arxiv.org/abs/2209.08989)\n\nReproduces Experiment A Figure 4 by comparing SK0WE/P’s 2.5 m center-loaded Difona vertical with SK0WE/1’s Hy-Gain AV620 at the same remote receiver in the same WSPR cycle. The simultaneous Hardware A/B reconstruction uses SK0WE/P at JO97 as Target and SK0WE/1 at JO97 as Reference. In TX Compare → Segment Insight, compare Figure 4 with the right-hand Joint-Spot ΔSNR histogram—not the middle Station Medians histogram. WSPRadar uses finer 1 dB bins and percent-of-sample bars, whereas the paper uses coarser density bins; consequently, the bars look somewhat different, but rebinning reconciles the two presentations. The 166 joint receiver-cycles give mean ΔSNR −6.78 dB with sample σ = 3.51 dB, essentially identical to the paper’s −6.8 dB and 3.5 dB. The sampled paths strongly favor the Reference vertical; this is relative path-sampled performance, not direction-independent antenna gain."
    }
  },
